Hunter [S1 - 9th] 2025-10-17 1:52 PM
this is what i cooked up, its legal according to rikav Rankor, The Redeemed God of the Souless In a not so distant future, People's lives are simultaneously liked, shared, and erased all at once. Through social media, small populations of robots learn about humans and their cultures and eventually begin to act like them. Some robots seek out humans in secret to study more of their ways. Other extreme, obsessive examples begin to emerge of cult-like behavior. Robots begin to abduct and experiment on humans, studying their anatomy and the ways they experience pain, torment, displeasure, and sadness. Naturally, they also begin to experiment on themselves, rewiring circuits so that they can feel pain, eventually leading to the practice of self-harm. Rankor, a religious bot studying at a human monastery, is abducted by the cult for teaching the opposite of their beliefs. He is then tortured and experiences extreme pain and sadness. He comes to believe he was wrong and that humans deserve to feel the same pain as him. He becomes the leader of the cult and devises a plan to attack the monastery. They attack the monastery, killing many and destroying many of the structures. He fights with one of the elder monks he studied with and, in a heat of rage, kills him, only to be immediately remorseful, the realization of what he had done to his home. In the aftermath of the attack, he kneels before a half-destroyed statue of Buddha and rips out his core. He loses power and dies.
1:52 PM
With tensions rising in areas across the globe, another robot named X travels to the monastery. He stumbles upon the sight of Rankor, core in hand, kneeling in front of the statue. He is who X was looking for. X brings Rankor to a secluded area and begins work on restoring him. However, it is not to his previous form as a student of religion and leader of the cult, but a reflection of both. His physical form remains largely the same, with the giant hole in his chest remaining. However, with memory of his past learnings and failures etched into his very existence, he is restored and transforms into a deity; Rankor, God of the Souless. With a steadily growing population of sentient robots, Rankor sets out to use his newfound understanding of the world and his growing influence as one who came back from the dead to steer his people through the human crisis. While feelings of contempt and reverence still swirl around in his head, he is determined to guide his people through war and division to create a unified Robot society.
1:52 PM
not completely finished or anything but thats the core

Kaitan [S1 - 11th] 2025-10-17 4:53 PM
Okay i wrote it
4:53 PM
Its very long....
4:53 PM
Rankor, The Redeemed God of the Souless In a not so distant future, People's lives are simultaneously liked, shared, and erased all at once. Through social media, small populations of robots learn about humans and their cultures and eventually begin to act like them. These bots at first just take shape as your average bot account you may run into on Instagram or other social media platforms. However as humans give them the time of day and interact with them, the bot evolves and transforms until is has evolved into a robotic model of a human. However that wasn't enough for some of the robots, some needed to understand more about humans, such as emotions. Robots begin to abduct and experiment on humans, studying their anatomy and the ways they experience pain, torment, displeasure, and sadness. Naturally, they also begin to experiment on themselves, rewiring circuits so that they can feel pain, eventually leading to the practice of self-harm.
4:54 PM
A particular bot, who at the time went by the name Rankor also began to obsess. However while other bots were fascinated by the human emotion, Rankor slowly began to delve into the concept of human religion. Rankor became fascinated by the words of priests, monks, and theologians, of all religions. They had a vision where someday they could become a deity to the robots, who didn't have an afterlife to look forward to. As Rankor began to speak a message of love, hope, and a future, to the other bots, the message wasn't well received by some groups of bots, who believed that the only way to experience the human emotion was through the deep pain and sorrow all humans go through at some point in their lives. These bots, blinded by their obsession successfully kidnapped Rankor and held them in their own temple, where they began to torment them, showing them a side of the world where hope was nowhere to be seen and there was no light at the end of the tunnel. Rankor, scarred by the horrors he had been forced to witness, and questioning why any god that represents hope for the future would permit such a dark present made a decision in their head that the afterworld was a far fetched tale. The more and more Rankor was tortured and beaten and bruised, the more it satisfied them? Like a moth to a light Rankor found themselves intrigued with the cult. And Rankor decided to join their ranks and join the cult.
4:54 PM
As Rankor involved themselves in the robots ranks, they began to go on "missions" where they would kidnap pther robots and do what was done to Rankor, endless torture. The more and more Rankor did this the more they became accustomed. And soon they began to find thrill in it, even going as far as torturing themselves and the other members of the cult. One fateful day however, Rankor recieved a mission where they met a robot like no other. The robot, who went by the name of X was a bright young bot. Hopeful, enthusiastic, and wise everything Rankor was and had now come to hate. But yet something about X made Rankor hesitate. Where as Rankor would usually immediately kidnap their victims, Rankor waited, playing a good guy, curious to see what X believed of the world.
4:55 PM
However Rankor's involvement in their life had doomed X from the start. Eventually a fellow member of Rankor's cult came and found X with Rankor. Rankor stood and watched as the bot they had come to know and almost care for, was tortured in front of their eyes. The torment was too much for a young bot like X and with their last source of power, they smiled faintly at Rankor and died. As the member of Rankor's cult walked away, Rankor was smacked with a feeling they had never felt before. Guilt. Tears of hot oil streamed down the bots face. They had thought the darkness was their answer but after watching X suffer and still smile through the pain they realized that hope will always be stronger than darkness. Flooded with guilt and self hatred for what they had done Rankor walked himself back to the cult hideout, oil still streaming down their metallic face, used their very own tears to set the place ablaze, killing them and everyone else in the cult. However, thats not where the story ended for Rankor.
4:55 PM
Little did Rankor realize that their fascination with deities of all sorts, had intrigued the very deities themselves, who were alive and present. Fascinated by their interest and belief of a god to represent the robots they followed their whole journey from start to end. So when Rankor had awoken they found themselves in a glorious room surrounded by the most infamous of patrons. A woman with a kind and gentle smile looked upon Rankor and smiled. She revealed herself to be Rikav, creator of the gods. Fascinated by their story and inspired by their sacrifice, Rikav granted Rankor the patron powers. And from that day on Rankor became the god of the soulless. They represented not only the robots, who are created with no true soul, but also those who because of darkness feel only emptiness in their soul. Rankor began to be worshipped by those who felt empty in hopes of a feeling of something anything that can change their life drastically, just like what happened in Rankors own life.
4:55 PM
Okay lmk what u all think
